│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### 1. Analysis of the Crash                                                                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ - **Trigger:** The crash occurs when running the `slp-vectorizer` pass on a specific piece of LLVM IR.                                                                                   │
│ - **IR Details:** The IR contains `getelementptr` (GEP) instructions in a basic block (`bb3`) whose indices are defined in a predecessor basic block (`bb`). Specifically, the indices   │
│ are `zext` and `sext` instructions.                                                                                                                                                      │
│ - **Stack Trace:** The crash happens in `llvm::slpvectorizer::BoUpSLP::getLastInstructionInBundle`, which is called during `vectorizeGEPIndices`. This indicates the vectorizer is       │
│ attempting to vectorize the indices of the GEP instructions.                                                                                                                             │
│ - **Assertion Failure:** The failing assertion is:                                                                                                                                       │
│   ```c++                                                                                                                                                                                 │
│   ((GatheredLoadsEntriesFirst.has_value() && ... ) ||                                                                                                                                    │
│    all_of(E->Scalars, [=](Value *V) -> bool {                                                                                                                                            │
│      if (E->getOpcode() == Instruction::GetElementPtr && !isa<GetElementPtrInst>(V))                                                                                                     │
│        return true;                                                                                                                                                                      │
│      auto *I = cast<Instruction>(V);                                                                                                                                                     │
│      return !E->isOpcodeOrAlt(I) || I->getParent() == BB || isVectorLikeInstWithConstOps(I);                                                                                             │
│    })) && "Expected gathered loads or GEPs or instructions from same basic block."                                                                                                       │
│   ```                                                                                                                                                                                    │
│ - **Root Cause:** The SLP vectorizer's `vectorizeGEPIndices` logic tries to group and vectorize the indices of GEP instructions. In this case, it groups the `zext` and `sext`           │
│ instructions from `bb` because they are used as indices by the GEPs in `bb3`. The problem arises when `getLastInstructionInBundle` is called. This function expects all scalar           │
│ instructions in a bundle to be in the same basic block as the instructions being vectorized (in this case, the GEPs in `bb3`), unless they are constants or meet other specific          │
│ criteria. The `zext` and `sext` instructions are in `bb`, not `bb3`, and they are not constants, causing the assertion to fail.                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### 2. Proposed Solution                                                                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The core issue is that `vectorizeGEPIndices` is trying to vectorize operands (the GEP indices) that are in a different basic block. This is a known limitation and a complex scenario    │
│ for the SLP vectorizer. A simple and safe fix is to prevent the vectorizer from attempting this when the indices are not in the same basic block as the GEPs.                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will modify `SLPVectorizer.cpp` within the `vectorizeGEPIndices` function. Before attempting to vectorize a list of GEP indices, I will add a check to ensure that all the index       │
│ instructions reside in the same basic block as the GEP instructions themselves. If they don't, we should skip vectorization for that group of indices.                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The relevant part of the code is a loop that iterates over potential GEP index bundles. Inside this loop, a list of values `VectorizableIndices` is created. I will iterate over this    │
│ list and check the parent basic block of each instruction.                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ // In llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, inside vectorizeGEPIndices:                                                                                                       │
│ ...                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│       if (VectorizableIndices.size() < 2)                                                                                                                                                │
│         continue;                                                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│       // I will add the check here.                                                                                                                                                      │
│       bool AllInBB = all_of(VectorizableIndices, [&](Value *V) {                                                                                                                         │
│         Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V);                                                                                                                                       │
│         return !I || I->getParent() == BB;                                                                                                                                               │
│       });                                                                                                                                                                                │
│       if (!AllInBB)                                                                                                                                                                      │
│         continue;                                                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│       if (tryToVectorizeList(VectorizableIndices, B, true))                                                                                                                              │
│         Changed = true;                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ ...                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│ This change ensures that we only proceed with vectorizing GEP indices if they are all defined in the current basic block (`BB`), which is the block containing the GEPs. This avoids the │
│ cross-block scenario that leads to the assertion failure.                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### 3. Implementation                                                                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will now apply this change using `sed`.                                                                                                                                                │
